   +pod('')
      .uk-width-medium-6-10
         p
            | The overwhelming majority of life on our planet depends on the sun for energy. Because life is so tightly linked to the sun, it is
            | no surprise that many organisms (excluding those that live in total darkness) have evolved the ability to detect and respond to
            | light. Plants turn their leaves toward the sun. Single-celled algae, protists, and other microbes swim toward or away from light.
            | But it is the animals, with our image-forming eyes, that have taken light detection to the next level.

         p
            | 96% of animal species have eyes. The first animal eyes did little but detect light&mdash;they helped to establish day/night
            | cycles and coordinate behavior&mdash;but more-complex eyes soon evolved. A predator who can see its prey from a distance, or a
            | prey animal that can see the shadow of a predator approaching, has a clear survival advantage over those who can&apos;t. Even a
            | slight improvement in image quality provides a significant survival advantage, allowing for the step-by-step evolution of
            | increasingly complex eyes.
      |    
      .uk-width-medium-4-10
         img(src='coralspawn.jpg', height='290', width='350', style='margin-bottom:0px;', alt='starfish on coral')

         p.uk-text-small
            | By synchronizing their reproductive cycles with the sun and the moon, some species of coral manage to spawn 
            | during a single hour of the year.  Light detection may have first evolved to set up rhythms and routines for feeding, 
            | movement, and reproduction. 
            em (Photo: Emma Hickerson, NOAA)
