   +pod('Light Detection, Pigment, and Movement Make an Eye')
      |    
      .uk-width-medium-4-10
         p
            | At its simplest, the eye incorporates three functions:
         ol(style='width:320px;')
            li Light detection
            | &#x9;&#x9;&#x9;&#x9;
            li
               | Shading, in the form of dark pigment, for sensing the direction light is coming from
            | &#x9;&#x9;&#x9;&#x9;
            li Connection to motor structures, for movement in response to light
         | &#x9;&#x9;&#x9;In some organisms, all three of these functions are carried out by just one cell&mdash;the single-celled euglena is one example. It has a light-sensitive spot, pigment granules for shading, and motor cilia. This structure, however, isn&apos;t considered a true eye. 
         br
         | &#x9;&#x9;&#x9;
         br
         | &#x9;&#x9;&#x9;The most-basic structure that is widely accepted as an eye has just two cells: a photoreceptor that detects light, and a pigment cell that provides shading. The photoreceptor connects to ciliated cells, which engage to move the animal in response to light. The marine ragworm embryo (right) has a two-celled eye.
         | &#x9;&#x9;&#x9;
         p
      |    
      .uk-width-medium-6-10
         img(src='two-celled-eye.jpg', height='332', width='489', alt='Two celled eye')

   +pod('The Evolution of Image-forming Eyes')

      .uk-width-medium-4-10
         p
            | An eye with more photoreceptors has more power: it can detect variations in light intensity across its surface. A
            | cup-shaped eye can better sense both the direction light is coming from and the movement of nearby objects. These
            | improvements require only minor changes to the basic eye.
         | &#x9;&#x9;
         p
            | As animals evolved more-complex bodies and behaviors, the eye too became more complex. Eyes evolved connections to
            | muscle cells rather than cells that moved by waving cilia. Neurons evolved that could process signals and coordinate
            | behavior.
         | &#x9;&#x9;
         p
            | Later improvements included structures for better optics, such as lenses or mirrors that gather and focus light onto
            | photoreceptors. Some eyes became spherical and evolved pupils that opened and closed to let in just the right amount
            | of light for forming clear images. Muscles evolved to fine-tune focusing and to point the eye in different directions.
            | Photoreceptors increased in number, providing more-detailed images (like adding pixels to a photograph).
      |    
      .uk-width-medium-6-10
         img(src='complexEyes.jpg', alt='complex eyes', height='333', width='490')

   +pod('Stepping Up to a Complex Eye')

      .uk-width-medium-4-10
         +well
            img(src='diverseEyes.jpg', height='106', width='320', alt='diverse eyes', style='margin-bottom:20px;')

            p
               | On the inside, diverse eyes use some of the very same components&mdash;a basic molecular &quot;toolkit&quot; for building an eye. However,
               | some structures that look alike, for example vertebrate and squid lenses, have different evolutionary origins.

            p
               | Learn more about the 
               a(href='http://learn.genetics.utah.edu/content/selection/toolkit/') molecular "toolkit" for building an eye
               | , and the genetic origin of eyes.
      |    
      .uk-width-medium-6-10
         p
            | Eyes most likely evolved from simple to complex through a gradual series of tiny steps. Piecing together the sequence of eye evolution is
            | challenging, and we don&apos;t know the sequence of steps that led to every modern eye. But we do know that modern animal eyes come in many
            | varieties, spanning a continuum from the simplest to the most complex. This demonstrates that all types of eyes are useful, and that eyes
            | of intermediate complexity could also have formed as steps in the evolution of complex eyes.
         |       
         p
            | Researchers at Lund University wanted to find out how long it might take for a complex eye to evolve. Starting with a flat, light-sensitive
            | patch, they gradually made over 1,800 tiny improvements&mdash;forming a cup, constricting the opening, adding a lens&mdash;until they had
            | a complex, image-forming eye. It is important to note that every tiny change these researchers made measurably improved image quality.
            | The researchers concluded that these steps could have taken place in about 360,000 generations, or just a few hundred thousand years. 550
            | million years have passed since the formation of the oldest fossil eyes, enough time for complex eyes to have evolved more than 1,500 times.
         | &#x9;&#x9;&#x9;&#x9;
         +well
            | To learn more, view the short video about 
            a(href='https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=duBW9QabXfw') how the eye could have evolved 
            | through a series of tiny steps.
 
